**UPDATE: I am of such a lowly SO status I canâ€™t comment on Kirkâ€™s post. I wasnâ€™t aware of Host being the preferred in 3.0. Anyway, Kirkâ€™s answer should be the correct one** 

You should be using WebHost (not Host) as follows:

```
public class Program
    {
        public static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            CreateWebHostBuilder(args).Build().Run();
        }

        public static IWebHostBuilder CreateWebHostBuilder(string[] args) =&gt;
            WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
                .UseStartup&lt;Startup&gt;();
    }

```

Take another look at the error message:

&gt; The type or namespace name &#39;CreateDefaultBuilder&#39; does not exist in the namespace &#39;Template.Host&#39;...

When you have `Host.CreateDefaultBuilder` in a namespace of `Template.Host`, the compiler assumes you mean `Template.Host.CreateDefaultBuilder`. There are at least the following approaches for fixing this:

1. Nest the `using` statement inside of your namespace:

        namespace Template.Host
        {
            using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
    
            // ...
        }

2. Alias the `Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting.Host` type inside of your namespace:

        namespace Template.Host
        {
            using Host = Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting.Host;
    
            // ...
        }

3. Use the full name of the `Host` type:

        Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting.Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)

`Host` represents the [Generic Host](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/fundamentals/host/generic-host?view=aspnetcore-3.0) and is preferred over [`WebHost`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/fundamentals/host/web-host?view=aspnetcore-3.0) in ASP.NET Core 3.0+.

