Not really, this data is not kept by the compiler. You would either create a separate class for lambda:
```
interface StringFunc extends Function&lt;String, String&gt; {}
```
And then you can get StringFunc super interface to get `Function&lt;String, String&gt;`.

Or just use classes instead of lambdas:

        printIt(new Function&lt;String, String&gt;() {
            @Override
            public String apply(String s) {
                return s;
            }
        });

Lambdas also generate synthetic method in the class they were declared in:

        Function&lt;String, String&gt; x = (String a) -&gt; a;
        printIt(x);
      
        for (Method declaredMethod : Test.class.getDeclaredMethods()) {
            if (declaredMethod.isSynthetic()) {
                System.out.println(declaredMethod);
            }
        }
    }

will print 

    public java.lang.Object org.gotofinal.Test$$Lambda$14/0x0000000800066840.apply(java.lang.Object)
    private static java.lang.String org.gotofinal.Test.lambda$main$0(java.lang.String)

But I don&#39;t see option to get declaration class of lambda (but can be extracted from class name) and how to match method with a lambda + it&#39;s implementation specific so might not work on every version of jvm. Also this method will include types of local variables passed to lambda:

        int dd = &quot;dddd&quot;.length() + args.length;
        Function&lt;String, String&gt; x = (String a) -&gt; a + dd;

will print: 

    private static java.lang.String org.gotofinal.Test.lambda$main$0(int,java.lang.String)


So probably your best bet is to just pass type as separate argument: 

    public &lt;F, T&gt; Whatever method(Class&lt;F&gt; typeF, Class&lt;T&gt; typeT, Function&lt;F, T&gt; func)

